apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 YUZHNO-SAKHALINSK, Russia, June 7 (Kyodo) At least 10% of the more than 20,000 residents of the southern Kuril Islands have left their homes since a strong earthquake rocked extensive areas of northern Japan and the chain of islands north of Hokkaido on Oct. 4 last year, a Russian official said Wednesday. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Most of the residents have moved to Sakhalin or the Russian mainland, the official of the state of Sakhalin said. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Anxiety about another large earthquake is growing among the remaining residents of the southern Kuril Islands following the recent earthquake that devastated parts of northern Sakhalin, the official said. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 The Russian government has already started a program to build 1,300 apartments for the residents who have moved or wish to move to other places, the official said, adding about 80% of the apartments have already been completed. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 The Oct. 4 earthquake, with amgnitude of 7.9 on the Richter scale, shook Etorofu, Kunashiri, Shikotan and the Habomai group of islets, all of which are claimed by Japan as its own territories, as well as a wide area of northern Japan. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 The temblor killed at least seven Russians and left more than 1,000 homeless as well as injuring more than 300 Japanese. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 On May 28, another earthquake measuring 7.5 on the Richter scale devastated the oil town of Neftegorsk on Sakhalin Island. 
